{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6f2b4aa0-4a1c-487b-993c-0d71067d3759","content":"There's no documentation on this topic in the current workspace, but I can answer from general .NET/macOS knowledge:\n\n**Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`:**\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS stores them in `/cores/` by default):\n   ```bash\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n\n3. **Reproduce the crash.** A `core.<pid>` file should appear in `/cores/`.\n\n4. **If `/cores/` is empty**, ensure SIP isn't blocking core dumps. Check with:\n   ```bash\n   csrutil status\n   ```\n\n5. **Analyze with `lldb`** (macOS's native debugger):\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n6. **Alternatively, use the macOS `ReportCrash` logs** at:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   These contain stack traces and register state automatically.\n\n**Key note:** NativeAOT apps don't bundle `createdump` (it's a CoreCLR component). The macOS kernel-level core dump (`/cores/`) or `ReportCrash` logs are your primary recovery paths.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e829a424-703b-42a7-b9f4-bdd59f97850a","outputTokens":326,"requestId":"A0CC:2C626E:952756:B79DD6:6A013709"},"id":"6446c5a7-a92f-4e57-8d1b-1b1780546321","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:55:29.214Z","parentId":"565068bb-4310-49fb-9c8c-4960ec09ce61"}
